recipeIngredient: Sea salt and pepper, to taste

recipeInstructions.name: Using a mandoline, slice the potatoes into fries....
recipeInstructions.text: Using a mandoline, slice the potatoes into fries. I don't worry too much about the size of fry I am making- some are bigger, and some are smaller. That's fine!

recipeInstructions.name: Next, place your spuds in a nice cool...
recipeInstructions.text: Next, place your spuds in a nice cool water bath. Completely submerge the fries in water.

recipeInstructions.name: Let fries sit one hour. This helps to...
recipeInstructions.text: Let fries sit one hour. This helps to remove excess starch and will help the fries crisp up more in the oven.

recipeInstructions.name: After an hour, drain the water, and pat...
recipeInstructions.text: After an hour, drain the water, and pat fries dry with a paper towel.

recipeInstructions.name: Toss with a couple tablespoons of olive oil,...
recipeInstructions.text: Toss with a couple tablespoons of olive oil, salt and pepper.

recipeInstructions.name: Add fries to bottom of air fryer basket,...
recipeInstructions.text: Add fries to bottom of air fryer basket, making sure they are all on the same level (don't stack them on top of each other.)
Cook 15-20 minutes, until crispy and golden brown.

recipeInstructions.name: Place on a baking sheet lined with paper...
recipeInstructions.text: Place on a baking sheet lined with paper towels and a cooling rack over it.

recipeInstructions.name: Place in warm oven (set to the minimum...
recipeInstructions.text: Place in warm oven (set to the minimum temperature, not over 250 degrees) and let rest while other batches of fries are cooking.
